<h2>HVAC Systems in Texas</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Texas presents unique HVAC challenges due to its diverse climate zones and extreme temperature variations. The state experiences hot, humid summers with temperatures regularly exceeding 100¬∞F, particularly in central and southern regions. Houston averages 96 days above 90¬∞F annually, while Dallas sees approximately 88 such days. This intense heat creates substantial cooling demands from May through September, with peak electrical loads occurring during afternoon hours when both residential and commercial air conditioning systems operate at maximum capacity.</p>

<p>Humidity levels vary dramatically across Texas, with eastern regions experiencing subtropical humidity levels above 70% during summer months, while western areas maintain more arid conditions below 30% relative humidity. This variation requires different HVAC approaches - eastern installations benefit from enhanced dehumidification capabilities, while western systems prioritize efficient cooling with minimal moisture removal. Winter heating requirements remain moderate across most of Texas, with northern regions requiring heating systems capable of handling occasional freezing temperatures, while southern areas need minimal heating capacity.</p>

<p>The combination of high temperatures, variable humidity, and extended cooling seasons makes energy efficiency paramount for Texas HVAC systems. Modern high-efficiency units with SEER ratings of 16-20 or higher can reduce cooling costs by 30-50% compared to older systems, while variable-speed technology allows precise temperature and humidity control. Integration with solar energy systems creates opportunities for net-zero energy cooling, where solar production offsets air conditioning consumption during peak demand periods.</p>

