<h2>Texas Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Texas residents have access to substantial incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and permitting fees, with no cap on the credit amount. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if the homeowner's tax liability is insufficient to claim the full amount in the installation year.</p>

<p>Texas offers a valuable property tax exemption for solar installations, meaning the added value from solar panels does not increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the life of the solar system. Additionally, Texas has no state income tax, which means residents can fully benefit from federal tax credits without state tax complications that affect homeowners in other states.</p>

<p>Oncor, serving over 10 million customers across Texas, provides various energy efficiency rebate programs for HVAC upgrades. The Oncor Energy Efficiency Program offers rebates up to \$2,500 for high-efficiency air conditioning systems, \$1,200 for heat pump installations, and \$300 for programmable thermostat upgrades. These rebates are available to qualifying residential customers who install ENERGY STAR certified equipment that meets specific efficiency requirements. Many local municipalities and electric cooperatives throughout Texas also offer additional rebate programs, with some providing rebates for solar battery storage systems and smart home energy management technologies.</p>

<p>Net metering policies vary across Texas utility territories, with some areas offering full retail rate credits for excess solar production while others provide wholesale rates. Time-of-use electricity plans can maximize solar savings by providing higher rates during peak afternoon hours when solar production is highest. The combination of federal tax credits, state property tax exemptions, utility rebates, and favorable electricity market structures creates an attractive financial environment for solar and HVAC investments in Texas.</p>

